We can see the overall usage in the United States of different resources, coal, oil, natural gas, and renewable sources, as a percentage of the total energy consumed for each year from 2000 to 2018 in the above scatterplot. To add a frame of reference, the purple line is the U.S. population in the 10 millions at that point in time. In order to determine if there was a relationship between population size and the overall electricity generated for the U.S. a Pearson correlation coefficient analysis was performed. A strong positive relationship was found with a correlation coefficient of 0.7808181 which denotes that the electricity generated was dependent upon the population over the years, and as the population grew, so did the electricity generated. We can further dive into the specifics of each resourceâs dependency on population throughout the years to predict which resource should be invested in. As we compare the above graphs and associated data, relationships between the population size and the use of specific resources over time are clear: the demand for natural gas and renewable sources grows with the population while the demand for coal and oil will decline with population growth. Investing in renewable sources of power generation may seem wise at this junction, and predictions for future growth would support those investments, but there is an important factor to analyze before that will happen.

Do Resources Impact Other Resources?

If one resourceâs utilization is impacted by the use of another than the predictions we will make need to factor that in, otherwise the investments cannot be made with certainty. The method by which we analyze the potential relationships will be an ANOVA test, which will compare the variability between our resources, accounting for the potential hidden interactions between the groups. Our ANOVA test, as can be seen below and is detailed on the side, revealed that the variability in our population data probably does not have a significant impact on our data and it could be due to randomness, especially when all values are taken into context. The unfortunate discovery from our test is the certainty with which we can say the resource consumption sources definitely has an impact on one another and any predictions we made are likely to be false due to high variability and interaction between the resources. While we would love to urge investment in âgreenâ energy sources due to our data, it is far more likely that the growth in renewable sources is also being affected by additional, unaccounted for variables. One probable cause could be the relatively recent push for more renewable sources being used to combat climate-change/global warming.

Woah! Those are some extreme numbers. Hereâs some insight behind them:

  • The values in the Sum Sq column illustrates how much variability is caused by the population, by the different resources, the interaction between those two categories, and the unexplained variability (from top to bottom) Higher values like those we see indicates the strength of impact.

  • The first two values in the Statistics column illustrates how significant the differences are between the population values and the different resources utilization values (respectively). The next value quantitatively ascertains the significance of the interaction between population and resource use.

  • The p.value column represents how likely the the values obtained were by chance. A p-value that is less than .05 is represents an unlikely probability that it was due to randomness and is likely significant, where a p-value that is less than .001 represents a high significance with it being extremely unlikely to be due to chance.
